WEBVTT

00:00.354 --> 00:01.175
Happy New Year.

00:03.159 --> 00:04.020
Good to see you all.

00:06.544 --> 00:13.817
We are in a new message series this morning that will last us about four weeks called the generous life.

00:15.780 --> 00:23.573
And I've been thinking about generosity and to start off this morning, I want to make a statement.

00:24.935 --> 00:26.578
I'm not exactly an optimist.

00:27.586 --> 00:33.352
But I do tend to try to believe the best about people, assume the best about people.

00:33.372 --> 00:41.080
And I think I believe that most of us don't struggle with the intent toward generosity.

00:42.422 --> 00:45.826
I think most of us struggle with priority.

00:47.728 --> 00:54.815
Most of us don't struggle with generosity because we're selfish people intending to be selfish.

00:55.236 --> 00:57.458
We struggle with generosity because

00:57.794 --> 00:58.876
Let's just face it, we're human.

01:00.698 --> 01:07.369
And we know what should come first in life, but we don't always tend to keep first things first.

01:08.250 --> 01:17.204
Not because we reject what matters most in life, but because the urgency of life has a way of crowding out our priorities.

01:18.586 --> 01:19.728
Pressure shows up.

01:20.389 --> 01:25.637
A need arises to the surface and a gap opens in a deadline looms.

01:25.697 --> 01:26.578
And slowly,

01:26.658 --> 01:53.330
almost without noticing something important gets pushed down the list not because it stopped mattering but because something else felt more immediate and I've had this play out in my own life in ministry I don't I don't work a real job this is what my job is and I'm kidding it is a real job but

01:53.634 --> 02:07.153
You know, I don't know if the rest of you are like me at all, but I tend to when I have my downtime, that's when I start to think about what's important, what matters, what I should be accomplishing, what my goals are, Corbin just talked about New Year's resolutions.

02:07.974 --> 02:10.378
I try to think about goals and things like that.

02:11.059 --> 02:17.107
And oftentimes as I'm thinking about those things, praying about them, I'll get really, really excited, really impassioned about it.

02:17.127 --> 02:19.250
And I'm like, all right, that's where I'm going.

02:20.482 --> 02:27.029
And one of those things that kind of comes natural for me is that I am a big believer in discipleship.

02:27.049 --> 02:31.955
I don't know if you know this, but in Matthew 28, Jesus tells his earliest disciples, you make disciples.

02:32.475 --> 02:33.997
It's kind of our big marching order.

02:34.758 --> 02:36.560
We're all supposed to be about disciple making.

02:37.340 --> 02:42.987
And so with my work in church, I tend to put disciple making first.

02:44.108 --> 02:49.714
But over the years, I've found that as stress has a way of distorting priorities

02:50.594 --> 03:05.015
Leadership vacuums open, pressure to fill roles increases, and before long, I find myself chasing other initiatives instead of focusing on the priority of forming disciples.

03:06.056 --> 03:13.948
In fact, I'll even start questioning, is this even what I'm supposed to be doing, even though it is the number one marching order that Jesus gave?

03:16.011 --> 03:18.194
And it's not because I stopped believing what was right.

03:18.786 --> 03:20.929
but because urgency displays priority.

03:22.311 --> 03:40.015
So if you are like me and you are a goal-oriented person or you think about what matters most to you, you might be the type of person that when the pressures of life come in, your priorities, the things that are supposed to come first get pressed downward.

03:41.797 --> 03:46.303
And these kinds of experiences have taught me something I need to be reminded of all the time.

03:46.964 --> 03:48.466
And that is that faith isn't just

03:48.546 --> 03:50.469
about knowing what matters most.

03:51.110 --> 03:53.333
It's not just about intention.

03:54.635 --> 03:56.838
It's about guarding what comes first.

03:58.901 --> 04:00.784
And this struggle isn't new for any of us.

04:01.745 --> 04:06.172
It shows up right at the beginning of the biblical story.

04:07.294 --> 04:10.679
I don't know about you, I like to read through the Bible year over year.

04:11.139 --> 04:12.381
So I'm back in Genesis again.

04:12.401 --> 04:18.450
And I just read through the story of Cain and Abel

04:19.426 --> 04:20.207
Genesis 4.

04:20.227 --> 04:23.531
And that's the story we're gonna look at today.

04:25.073 --> 04:30.520
Because that first family, Adam and Eve, they have children.

04:32.062 --> 04:39.992
And in this story of this first family comes the first opportunity where we see something by way of first fruits being offered.

04:41.454 --> 04:48.242
And it's in that story in Genesis 4 where God reveals something crucial about the heart

04:48.642 --> 04:50.164
behind what we bring to Him.

04:52.568 --> 04:56.654
Now Genesis 4, I'm going to be honest, is not a story that's primarily about generosity.

04:57.615 --> 05:09.834
It's a story about priority, about what we bring God, and what that reveals about who and what we trust.

05:11.576 --> 05:13.840
So this morning I want us to go back to the beginning.

05:14.280 --> 05:18.226
This Genesis 4 story, not to the beginning of generosity,

05:18.466 --> 05:22.151
but the beginning of worship.

05:22.171 --> 05:28.560
Genesis 4 introduces the first offerings ever recorded in scripture.

05:29.561 --> 05:34.808
And what we learn in this story sets a pattern that echoes throughout the rest of the Bible.

05:36.170 --> 05:47.986
As we go through this series called the Generous Life, we're going to trace from the beginning all the way through the New Testament story about this idea of being

05:48.098 --> 05:52.184
But I want us to start in this story in Genesis 4.

05:52.204 --> 05:56.730
So if you have her Bibles with you, we're going to be in the first 10 verses of Genesis 4.

05:56.790 --> 05:58.713
I'm going to jump right in and read it now.

06:01.557 --> 06:04.501
Says, the man Adam was intimate with his wife, Eve.

06:05.603 --> 06:07.846
And she conceived and gave birth to Cain.

06:08.907 --> 06:13.394
She said, I have made a man, I have made a male child with the Lord's help.

06:14.435 --> 06:16.498
She also gave birth to his brother Abel.

06:16.994 --> 06:21.480
Now Abel became a shepherd of flocks, but Cain worked the ground.

06:22.522 --> 06:27.849
In the course of time, Cain presented some of the land's produce as an offering to the Lord.

06:28.550 --> 06:34.319
And Abel also presented an offering, some of the first born of his flock, and their fat portions.

06:35.280 --> 06:41.209
And the Lord had regard for Abel and his offering, but he did not have regard for Cain and his offering.

06:42.050 --> 06:45.074
Cain was furious, and he looked despondent.

06:46.274 --> 06:49.399
Then the Lord said to Cain, why are you furious?

06:50.300 --> 06:51.683
And why do you look despondent?

06:52.884 --> 06:55.128
If you do what is right, won't you be accepted?

06:56.470 --> 07:02.079
But if you do not do what is right, sin is crouching at the door.

07:02.600 --> 07:06.426
Its desire is for you, but you must rule over it.

07:07.508 --> 07:11.494
And Cain said to his brother Abel, let's go out to the field.

07:12.415 --> 07:14.098
And while they were in the field,

07:14.402 --> 07:17.826
Cain attacked his brother Abel and killed him.

07:19.729 --> 07:23.613
Then the Lord said to Cain, where is your brother Abel?

07:25.115 --> 07:28.539
I don't know, he replied, am I my brother's guardian?

07:31.042 --> 07:32.945
Then he said, what have you done?

07:33.005 --> 07:37.170
Your brother's blood cries out to me from the ground.

07:39.874 --> 07:44.780
Now Genesis tells us that Cain and Abel both brought offerings to the Lord.

07:45.782 --> 07:59.119
Cain brings from produce from the ground, that was his work, and Abel brings from the first born of his flock, and from their fat portions, the best parts of what he had to offer.

08:00.821 --> 08:02.624
And notice something in this story.

08:03.585 --> 08:07.570
The text doesn't tell us that Cain brought something sinful to God.

08:09.058 --> 08:10.941
It doesn't say his offering was illegal.

08:11.842 --> 08:15.688
It simply says that he brought some of the produce.

08:16.850 --> 08:19.233
Abel, on the other hand, brings the first and the best.

08:20.155 --> 08:20.836
And this matters.

08:22.318 --> 08:25.102
The difference isn't agricultural versus livestock.

08:25.883 --> 08:28.127
It wasn't that one had a better job than the other.

08:28.828 --> 08:35.698
God accepts grain offerings elsewhere in scripture to the same level that he would have accepted Abel's offering.

08:36.482 --> 08:41.207
The difference between their offerings to God are about priority.

08:42.268 --> 08:52.217
This passage is not teaching that God prefers one profession over another, and it's not teaching that God arbitrarily favors one person over another.

08:52.237 --> 08:58.063
The text draws our attention to what Abel brought first.

08:58.964 --> 08:59.624
Firstborn.

09:00.525 --> 09:01.446
Fat portions.

09:02.267 --> 09:04.409
Language of intentionality.

09:04.989 --> 09:05.650
Trust.

09:06.018 --> 09:08.241
honor and priority.

09:10.024 --> 09:19.298
And then later in the New Testament, actually if you read the book of Hebrews, the offer of Hebrews tells us that Abel's offering was brought by faith.

09:19.719 --> 09:25.888
Hebrews 11-4 says this, says, by faith Abel offered to God a better sacrifice than Cain did.

09:26.849 --> 09:35.442
By faith, he was approved as a righteous man because God approved his gifts and even though he is dead, he still speaks through

09:35.682 --> 09:39.186
his faith.

09:39.206 --> 09:43.191
This means that Abel trusted God with what came first.

09:44.132 --> 09:49.178
Cain brought something but not in the same posture of trust as his brother Abel.

09:50.199 --> 10:00.171
So what Genesis is showing us isn't that worship is about what we give, it's about how and why we give, what we give.

10:01.133 --> 10:05.618
First fruit's giving isn't about generosity as much as it is about faith.

10:05.794 --> 10:12.280
and priority, it says that God is trusted by us with what comes next.

10:13.902 --> 10:25.414
Abel gives in a way that acknowledges God first, and Cain gives in a way that holds something back, not necessarily out of malice, but out of hesitation.

10:26.855 --> 10:33.842
And so what happens next, as we just read in Genesis 4, 6 or 7, is that one of the most gracious moments in the story.

10:33.954 --> 10:37.438
God does not immediately reject Cain as a person.

10:38.259 --> 10:39.080
He speaks to him.

10:41.243 --> 10:46.890
Again, he says, then the Lord said to Cain, why are you furious and why do you look despondent?

10:47.771 --> 10:50.014
If you do what is right, won't you be accepted?

10:50.054 --> 10:57.503
But if you do not do what is right, sin is crouching at the door and its desires for you, but you must rule over it.

10:59.465 --> 11:03.250
God is trying to tell Cain it's not to

11:03.458 --> 11:03.818
Late.

11:06.282 --> 11:08.425
Acceptance is still available.

11:09.026 --> 11:11.629
Repentance is still possible.

11:12.510 --> 11:14.593
The issue isn't the offering alone.

11:14.633 --> 11:16.015
It's the posture behind it.

11:16.836 --> 11:18.378
God doesn't shame Cain.

11:19.099 --> 11:24.307
He warns him, sin is crouching at the door, but you must rule over it.

11:25.849 --> 11:27.611
And Cain's struggle isn't greed.

11:28.853 --> 11:29.714
It's resentment.

11:30.978 --> 11:33.601
He doesn't just feel disappointed, he feels threatened.

11:33.641 --> 11:38.245
And when priority slips, comparison often follows.

11:39.686 --> 11:41.408
Love to play the comparison game.

11:43.950 --> 11:50.557
Whether we're looking at somebody else's lesser than us, or we're looking up to somebody that we don't feel we measure up to.

11:50.617 --> 11:52.739
And that's what Cain is doing here.

11:53.279 --> 11:57.143
So he refuses to listen to God's warning and instead escalates the issue.

11:58.204 --> 12:00.146
He's jealous of his brother

12:00.546 --> 12:03.029
in God's view of his brother's actions.

12:03.750 --> 12:07.794
So Cain said to his brother Abel, let's go out into the field.

12:08.655 --> 12:12.920
And when they were in the field, Cain rose up against his brother Abel and killed him.

12:14.321 --> 12:16.724
And then the Lord said to Cain, where's your brother Abel?

12:17.925 --> 12:21.609
And then he says, I do not know, am I my brother's keeper?

12:22.470 --> 12:24.592
Am I my brother's guardian?

12:24.633 --> 12:29.618
That's a pretty major question

12:29.858 --> 12:31.620
in Scripture alone?

12:31.680 --> 12:44.013
The answer ought to be yes, but Cain was more and more concerned with his own position before God and his jealousy against his brother.

12:44.053 --> 12:53.023
And what began as misplaced worship turned into misplaced anger and eventually into violence.

12:53.043 --> 12:59.250
And Genesis is showing us that when worship is distorted, relationships become damaged.

12:59.522 --> 13:06.169
A heart that resists trusting God often turning and ends up turning inward or outward in destructive ways.

13:08.312 --> 13:08.952
Happy New Year.

13:11.135 --> 13:14.578
Now I know that this is a sobering passage to start out the New Year.

13:16.701 --> 13:21.106
But it's not because God is harsh, but because our hearts are fragile.

13:22.887 --> 13:28.914
And when first things slip, second things start carrying weight that they were never meant to bear.

13:30.658 --> 13:35.683
Genesis 4 teaches us that first-fruits giving is never about earning God's favor.

13:36.263 --> 13:39.146
It's about acknowledging God's place in our lives.

13:40.467 --> 13:56.943
When Corbin was talking about this one New Year's resolution, keeping Jesus at the center, keeping God first, ables offering in the Genesis 4 story reflects first-fruits faith.

13:58.524 --> 14:00.146
It keeps God as priority.

14:00.642 --> 14:04.246
And it also shows trust that God will provide what comes next.

14:06.128 --> 14:15.418
And Cain's offering reflects hesitation, a holding back that eventually reveals a deeper struggle of the heart.

14:15.438 --> 14:19.102
And Genesis then shows us the danger of misaligned priorities.

14:19.883 --> 14:24.048
It shows us what happens when trust slips up, not all at once, but subtly.

14:25.129 --> 14:27.511
And Genesis doesn't leave us with a warning alone.

14:28.553 --> 14:29.874
Later in scripture,

14:30.114 --> 14:36.180
The wisdom literature of the Proverbs picks up the same theme and it says, here is how to live differently.

14:36.240 --> 14:39.704
Here's how to keep God as priority number one.

14:39.904 --> 14:47.852
Proverbs three, nine through 10, it says as follows, does honor the Lord with your possessions and with the first produce of your entire harvest.

14:48.653 --> 14:53.898
Then your barns will be completely filled and your vats will overflow with new wine.

14:55.620 --> 14:58.002
Now I know it happens when we read these Proverbs.

14:58.562 --> 15:00.785
We like to think in terms of contract language.

15:01.847 --> 15:04.571
If I do A, then God will come through with B.

15:04.631 --> 15:10.880
And so we start thinking not about what we give into this situation, but we get out of it.

15:12.482 --> 15:13.744
But I want to stop us right there.

15:13.784 --> 15:15.547
Proverbs is not a contract.

15:15.607 --> 15:18.892
It's not a guarantee of instant prosperity.

15:18.912 --> 15:23.378
The prosperity gospel is a false gospel.

15:25.986 --> 15:33.518
What Proverbs is saying in its wisdom is that God's invitation to live in reality is the way he intended and designed it.

15:35.201 --> 15:37.725
It does not say give so God will make you rich.

15:38.286 --> 15:42.012
It says honor God first and then trust him with what will follow after.

15:44.096 --> 15:52.850
To honor the Lord means to treat him as weighty, as first, as central, as worthy of trust.

15:54.370 --> 15:57.113
First fruit's giving is not about the size of the gift.

15:58.054 --> 16:00.196
It's about the order of the gift.

16:01.237 --> 16:05.342
In the ancient world, first fruit's offering was an act of faith.

16:05.822 --> 16:09.286
You gave before you knew the rest of the harvest would turn out.

16:10.427 --> 16:17.134
You acknowledge that everything belongs to God and that your future depended on Him, not your storehouses.

16:18.816 --> 16:20.978
And wisdom says something surprising.

16:21.570 --> 16:24.394
Giving first does not diminish the harvest.

16:25.256 --> 16:26.377
It consecrates it.

16:26.958 --> 16:27.839
It gives it meaning.

16:27.880 --> 16:30.083
It declares it to be sacred.

16:32.386 --> 16:37.815
So when Proverbs says barns will be filled and vats will overflow, it's not promising luxury.

16:37.835 --> 16:41.640
It's describing sufficiency, stability.

16:42.281 --> 16:46.708
God's faithful provision for a life lived and reverent trust.

16:48.411 --> 16:50.674
Wisdom teaches that when God is honored

16:51.042 --> 16:55.626
First, anxiety loosens its grip.

16:56.067 --> 17:00.591
And a heart that trusts God is freer, steadier, and more generous.

17:01.612 --> 17:06.437
Cain brought something after time passed, but Abel brought the first.

17:07.337 --> 17:10.280
Proverbs names the difference, Genesis only shows us.

17:11.101 --> 17:15.205
The honoring God first is an act of faith, not fear.

17:17.567 --> 17:20.690
But even as Proverbs gives us this wisdom for living,

17:21.602 --> 17:31.135
It also exposes a bit of a problem, because if we're honest, we don't always honor God first, or maybe I'm the only one.

17:33.538 --> 17:41.169
Even when we want to, even when we know it's the better thing, the best thing, and that raises an important question for us.

17:41.850 --> 17:43.893
What happens when our offerings fall short?

17:44.413 --> 17:46.817
What happens when our faith wavers?

17:47.698 --> 17:50.642
This is where the Bible does something beautiful.

17:51.042 --> 17:51.923
something gracious.

17:52.725 --> 17:55.328
It doesn't just tell us to give better offerings.

17:57.372 --> 17:59.475
It tells us that God already gave a perfect one.

18:01.738 --> 18:05.043
Scripture calls Jesus the first fruits.

18:07.867 --> 18:16.881
Not just the first to rise, but the representative gift offered on our behalf.

18:16.901 --> 18:20.146
Abel's offering was accepted because it was brought in faith.

18:20.322 --> 18:23.605
But Jesus didn't just bring an offering.

18:23.665 --> 18:26.848
He was the offering.

18:27.489 --> 18:31.953
Where Cain and Abel brought gifts to God, God brought his son to us.

18:33.775 --> 18:37.639
God did not wait to see how things might turn out before acting.

18:37.699 --> 18:40.601
He did not give leftovers.

18:41.222 --> 18:42.804
He did not hold back.

18:44.625 --> 18:49.490
As Paul says in Romans, while we were still sinners, God gave us.

18:49.794 --> 18:53.278
Jesus, Christ died for us.

18:54.240 --> 19:07.917
And Jesus is God's first and best gift, given not when it was safe, but when it was costly, which means our giving is never about paying God back.

19:07.937 --> 19:09.619
We don't give to earn acceptance.

19:10.380 --> 19:15.026
We give from acceptance that he's already given us.

19:16.130 --> 19:24.443
And we honor God with our first fruits, not because we're trying to secure His favor, but because His favor has already been secured for us in Christ.

19:27.007 --> 19:43.794
So if we had to say all of this in one sentence, if we had to name what God is inviting us into in this generous life, it would be this, that God, that honoring God first is an act of trust that reshapes everything else in our lives.

19:44.898 --> 19:50.005
Generosity becomes a response to grace, not a transaction to earn favor.

19:52.428 --> 19:58.236
Worship is what we do when we make God our first priority.

20:00.199 --> 20:02.061
We trust rather than fear.

20:02.842 --> 20:05.786
And when we give first, we're not proving our faith, we're practicing it.

20:07.409 --> 20:11.314
And wherever you are with generosity, there is one faithful next step.

20:12.450 --> 20:14.773
Not to impress God, but to trust Him.

20:15.835 --> 20:18.619
And that raises a simple, honest question for each of us.

20:19.460 --> 20:25.690
Not how much should I give, but what does trust in God look like in my life right now?

20:27.793 --> 20:35.985
Because I don't really want to be talking about numbers or percentages right now because we need something more clear stated at the outset.

20:36.306 --> 20:38.749
God is not after your money.

20:38.809 --> 20:42.034
He's after your trust.

20:43.042 --> 20:46.126
and trust rarely grows in one giant leap.

20:46.727 --> 20:50.571
It grows through faithful, intentional steps, sometimes small.

20:52.494 --> 20:56.739
So to lay this out for some of us, the idea of giving a tie feels familiar.

20:57.220 --> 21:04.269
For others, it feels overwhelming, especially if you're currently giving little or nothing at all.

21:04.289 --> 21:07.272
So I want us to talk about this way scripture does.

21:07.392 --> 21:09.235
As a matter of first things, not pressure.

21:10.296 --> 21:11.858
In scripture, first fruits,

21:12.066 --> 21:14.629
weren't about hitting a percentage before God would approve.

21:16.070 --> 21:19.674
They were about putting God first before everything else had a claim.

21:20.434 --> 21:21.856
Cain didn't bring nothing.

21:23.637 --> 21:24.879
He brought something to God.

21:26.380 --> 21:32.666
But Abel brought the first and the best in offering that was shaped by trust.

21:33.607 --> 21:40.434
So if you're not giving anything right now, the step God may be inviting you into is not to jump

21:40.738 --> 21:41.780
all the way up to 10%.

21:44.825 --> 21:51.876
It's a first step, a deliberate prayerful act that says, God, I'm choosing to trust you with this part of my life.

21:53.819 --> 21:57.124
That might mean starting with a small percentage.

21:58.386 --> 22:00.469
If you're going from zero, you ain't going to 10.

22:01.331 --> 22:03.254
Maybe you're going zero to one, zero to two.

22:04.215 --> 22:06.479
But you're doing it intentionally as an act of worship.

22:07.120 --> 22:08.402
Not to check a box,

22:08.578 --> 22:13.123
Not to impress God, but to begin putting first things first.

22:14.524 --> 22:19.230
Some of us give, but only when it feels comfortable, or when there's extra leftover.

22:19.810 --> 22:22.633
Proverbs calls us to something deeper than leftovers.

22:23.614 --> 22:27.699
It invites us to give first before the rest of the budget speaks.

22:28.700 --> 22:30.922
And for you, the next step might be consistency.

22:31.723 --> 22:33.846
This was my struggle point when I came to faith.

22:35.387 --> 22:37.970
When it was easy, I did it, and when it was not

22:38.146 --> 22:39.247
easy, I didn't.

22:40.950 --> 22:43.914
This is an issue that took a long while for me to come around to.

22:45.836 --> 22:52.365
And so when you're in this place, it's about consistency, choosing something and sticking to it.

22:53.426 --> 22:56.911
It's not about perfection, but it's about intentionality and direction.

22:57.912 --> 23:03.660
And for those of you that give regularly, even sacrificially, this passage still speaks to you.

23:04.741 --> 23:05.522
First fruits

23:05.826 --> 23:15.557
isn't just about what you give, but how you give, with joy, with trust, with gratitude, with open hands, as we'll see a little bit later in the New Testament.

23:16.277 --> 23:18.580
The question isn't, am I meeting a standard?

23:20.102 --> 23:25.387
It's, is my giving still an expression of trust, or has it become thoughtless and automatic?

23:27.490 --> 23:31.374
No matter where you are at with this, we all need to remember this.

23:32.135 --> 23:35.058
We do not give to earn God's blessing.

23:36.514 --> 23:41.419
We give because Christ has already given himself fully to us.

23:42.580 --> 23:45.643
Jesus is the true first fruit.

23:45.663 --> 23:54.812
God gave his first and best, not after we proved ourselves, but while we were still in need.

23:56.454 --> 23:59.096
So here's a question I want us to carry this week.

23:59.116 --> 24:02.800
What would it look like for each of us to trust God first?

24:04.201 --> 24:05.042
Not perfectly.

24:05.762 --> 24:08.586
but faithfully with what he's already given us.

24:11.310 --> 24:17.778
Now, as I said before, this is a heart matter that took me a while when I came to faith.

24:17.858 --> 24:25.229
I came to faith as a late teenager, and I married someone that had been in the faith for a lot longer than me.

24:27.151 --> 24:33.620
And so for my wife, this particular subject was like a non-starter.

24:33.640 --> 24:35.122
It was like, this is what you do.

24:36.418 --> 24:40.683
For me, it was like, this is really hard to let go of what I have.

24:42.204 --> 24:52.555
And so when we got married, we made a commitment to give regularly in church, especially considering I was gonna go into ministry and I felt really weird asking other people to do things I wouldn't do myself.

24:55.138 --> 24:56.039
And then 2008 hit.

24:58.382 --> 24:59.363
Y'all remember 2008?

24:59.423 --> 25:02.546
It feels like yesterday.

25:03.202 --> 25:08.908
Or maybe that's because yesterday feels like 2008 because anyway, anyway, I won't get into all that.

25:09.830 --> 25:15.496
You know, the feeling, especially after the holidays, wasn't this a great way to start?

25:18.099 --> 25:24.726
Angie and I were still early in marriage in 2008 and the economy had shifted really hard.

25:25.888 --> 25:31.474
We hit a recession and I remember sitting in my boss's office

25:32.002 --> 25:34.045
at the job at the bank that I was working at.

25:35.247 --> 25:42.758
And the company was debating whether to do layoffs or to cut people's hours back so that everyone could keep their jobs.

25:44.140 --> 25:53.534
Either way, somebody was losing something and it just mattered, it just came down to who was going to lose more.

25:53.554 --> 25:56.338
And suddenly everything felt tighter and less predictable.

25:57.954 --> 26:03.542
And if I'm honest, that was the season when trusting God with giving felt hardest, not easiest.

26:05.845 --> 26:07.046
I knew what scripture said.

26:07.066 --> 26:13.054
I believed that God was faithful, but belief didn't erase fear.

26:14.116 --> 26:17.320
And if you know me in my story, I am a person that deals with anxiety.

26:19.663 --> 26:22.046
Obedience doesn't mean the questions disappear.

26:24.109 --> 26:27.634
What I remember most clearly is the tension that was inside me at that time.

26:28.546 --> 26:35.135
What if I give first and God doesn't come through the way that I'm hoping?

26:36.697 --> 26:40.262
What if this ends up hurting us instead of helping us?

26:42.165 --> 26:52.339
And yet that season taught me something I'm still learning today, especially in times like these, because 2026 feels an awful lot like 2008 to me.

26:53.581 --> 26:54.322
Anybody agree?

26:59.010 --> 27:09.981
When the economy feels uncertain and costs keep rising, we are still called to remember that obedience comes before peace.

27:13.164 --> 27:16.648
Peace is wonderful, but it's fragile.

27:18.970 --> 27:19.931
Obedience is sturdier.

27:22.013 --> 27:24.136
I didn't feel calm when we chose to give.

27:24.156 --> 27:26.578
I felt exposed.

27:27.874 --> 27:36.267
I still struggle today in this moment in time with the questions I was experiencing all the way back in LA.

27:37.949 --> 27:50.929
But looking back, I can honestly say that God proved faithful, not always in the ways I expected, not even always in the way that I hoped, but consistently faithful.

27:53.012 --> 27:54.354
Still standing, I think.

27:56.386 --> 27:58.449
And here's the part I want you to hear clearly.

27:59.932 --> 28:01.774
That decision didn't make me fearless.

28:02.916 --> 28:07.644
I don't stand here before you acting like I got it all together, because trust me, I don't.

28:11.430 --> 28:16.177
It didn't make giving easy, but it did reshape my trust.

28:17.900 --> 28:24.530
And even now in a season where many of us are feeling the pressure again, literally just talking to my buddy Brad,

28:24.738 --> 28:26.680
about the pressure of the holiday season.

28:28.963 --> 28:29.904
We just came out of it.

28:30.545 --> 28:32.227
Everything feels unstable.

28:34.850 --> 28:37.614
And I feel that familiar pool that I did back then.

28:38.475 --> 28:44.663
The urge to hold tighter, to protect myself, to wait until things feel safer.

28:45.944 --> 28:48.207
And I still have to come back to the same question.

28:49.649 --> 28:54.034
Will I keep first things first?

28:55.298 --> 29:06.068
because that generous life is not about the percentage, how much I give, or about how stable life feels.

29:07.089 --> 29:09.992
It's about keeping first things first.

29:11.533 --> 29:12.154
Will I do it?

29:13.535 --> 29:16.618
The beautiful thing about this is that God did.

29:18.660 --> 29:22.284
He sent his son before we made the first move.

29:23.705 --> 29:24.946
While we were yet sinners,

29:26.818 --> 29:27.739
So what will I do?

29:27.799 --> 29:33.968
Not to make up for it, but in response.

29:34.569 --> 29:35.851
Well, I keep first things first.

29:36.491 --> 29:44.062
Each week we take communion to remember that God sent his son Jesus while we were yet sinners.

29:46.205 --> 29:55.538
We remember God's generosity that he sent his one and only son so that we could have abundant life to the full.

29:57.634 --> 30:20.969
And so when we take the bread and eat and we drink of the cup, we proclaim God's goodness, his grace, his generosity toward us that he sent his first fruits, the first fruit to save our lives so that we have life to the full.

30:22.512 --> 30:26.578
So I invite you to take a moment to pause and to reflect on the goodness of God

30:27.234 --> 30:32.189
that God made the first move so that we could respond in faith and trust.

30:32.710 --> 30:36.562
And after that moment of reflection, we will take communion together as one church family.

31:28.962 --> 31:35.528
I invite each and every one of you to take the bread and eat this represents his body which is given for us.

31:43.015 --> 31:46.218
And likewise I invite you to take and drink from this cup.

31:46.239 --> 31:48.561
This represents his blood which is poured out for us.

31:54.907 --> 31:55.607
Please pray with me.

31:57.549 --> 31:58.290
Dear Lord God,

31:59.650 --> 32:01.553
Thank you for being good to us.

32:03.575 --> 32:07.501
I thank you for being generous, for having grace, for having mercy.

32:09.964 --> 32:29.170
And for showing us a story that's uncomfortable to read in scripture for a whole host of reasons, that raises so many questions, and really pokes and prods at not only the challenges of our life, but our frailty of faith as human beings,

32:30.658 --> 32:55.762
But I thank you that in your gospel that you don't make our renewed relationship with you dependent on our work, but on the faithfulness of your son, Jesus, that you made the move while we were still far from you because you wanted us close to you.

32:57.090 --> 33:05.740
And so Lord, I pray for each and every one of us, no matter where we're at in this year, where we're considering what it looks like to put you first.

33:06.681 --> 33:10.565
We come face to face with the story and the early part of scripture.

33:11.987 --> 33:17.713
And I pray, Lord, that you will help us to see that this is not a competition.

33:17.773 --> 33:25.362
It's not about who's better, who's more faithful, but it's merely a conversation between

33:26.274 --> 33:36.528
you and us, and what it looks like to put you first in all facets of our life, including the things that we might want to hold most tightly to.

33:37.249 --> 33:53.091
So I pray for everybody in this room, myself included, that we will learn from this scripture, but more importantly, this call to keep you first will be enacted in our lives, not only here, together, but in every opportunity that we have.

33:54.333 --> 33:54.994
We love you.

33:55.074 --> 33:57.301
and we praise you and it's in your Son Jesus name, we pray.

33:57.990 --> 33:58.354
Amen.

